d, United Kingdom","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Orchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Urquhart","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."]},{"name":"Orahood","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Orchard   3, itself a rare English variant of Scottish   Urquhart  .","History: The Orahoods can trace their origin to Alexander, Joshua, and Thomas Orahood, who in the second half of the 18th century lived in VA and are believed to come to America from Scotland. Their surname is also listed in the forms <i>Orrahud</i>, <i>Arahood</i>, <i>Arrowhood</i>, and <i>Orchard</i>, the last one being the most likely original form."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Orchard was born on 7 February 1330, in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Orchard, was 38 and his mother, Elizabeth Wilton, was 31. He married Alice of England in 1345, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1397, in his hometown, at the age of 67, and was buried in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"7 February 1330–1397":"7. veebruar 1330–1397","1330–1397":"1330–1397","1326–1380":"1326–1380","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1291–1341":"1291–1341","1299–1364":"1299–1364","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1380":"1380","1291":"1291","7 February 1330":"7. veebruar 1330","1326":"1326","1346":"1346","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","Taunton Manor, Somerset, Engla